                <head>No. 144.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName corresp="#p_GB1" type="from">Bancroft</persName>
                        to Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HF1" type="to">Fish</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1873-08-01">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 1, 1873</date>. (Received August
                        22.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 507.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The newspapers have published a story that the
                    Duke of Hesse Darmstadt, on celebrating the twenty-fifth anniversary of his
                    reign, had <pb facs="0383" n="297" xml:id="pg_297"/> pardoned two criminals on
                    condition of their emigrating to America. After the correspondence that has
                    passed between the Darmstadt government and the legation at Berlin, I could not
                    believe it; but I thought proper to bring it to the notice of the Grand Duke’s
                    ministry. I have received a reply authorizing me officially to deny the truth of
                    the allegation.</p>
                <p>I remain, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GB1">GEO. BANCROFT</persName>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
